In this notebook we will see some common applications of vector norms in data science. It's important to consider that the limit of their use is just in our heads. They can serve for infinite purposes in several projects.

Also we will add how to calculate Linear Regression with vectors and matrices and not just with the function from the Scikit Learn library.

To sum up, first we will see how vector norms play a role in some predicting algorithms as regularizers and then how we use them to assess regression model's predictions measuring error.

Regularization¶

In this section we see how vector norms plays a role in three different algorithms that use them as a penalty term. For this we will use the Diabetes dataset that can be download from Scikit Learn.

Output¶

Next, we will see the impact of changing the value of the regularizer feature in predicting models that use vector norms for this purpose. The regalurization term is a cost in the optimization function of the algorithm that seek an optimal unique solution.

The models are: LASSO, Ridge and ElasticNet. LASSO use the L1 norm as a penalty, the cost function, because encourage solutions were many model's parameters are assigned to zero. Ridge uses the L2 norm as a penalty because encourage solutions were most parameter values are small. ElasticNet uses a combination of both, L1 and L2 norm.

LASSO uses the mean square error (MSE) and the penalty $\lambda$ for L1:

$C = \frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2 + \lambda \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{m} |w_j|$

Ridge also use MSE and $\lambda$ for L2:

$C = \frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2 + \lambda \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{m} |w_j|^2$

ElasticNet uses both and a $\alpha$ to assign probabilities:

$C = \frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2 + \lambda \lbrack \alpha \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{m} |w_j| + (1 - \alpha) \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{m} |w_j|^2 \rbrack$

We are going to run each algorithm 10 times in order to see the effect of changing $\lambda$ from 0.01 to 1.09 in each model.

This is going to be represented in a 10 different plots, one beside each other, for each model with a vertical line in the minimum error value in each plot.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet, LassoLars, Ridge

def reg_output(model,name):

    import numpy as np
    import pandas as pd
    from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
    from sklearn.datasets import load_diabetes
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

    def p_norm(vector,p):
        return sum(abs(vector)**p)**(1/p)

    plt.figure(figsize=(30,10))
    for i in range(10):

        data = load_diabetes()
        X, y = data.data, data.target
        X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.2)

        preds = {}
        for alpha_value in np.arange(0.01,1.1,0.01):

            modelo = model(alpha=alpha_value)
            modelo_fit = modelo.fit(X_train,y_train)
            pred = modelo_fit.predict(X_test)
            preds[f'{alpha_value}'] = pred

        errores = []
        for key in list(preds.keys()):
            errores.append((round(float(key),2),round(p_norm(vector=preds[key]-y_test,p=5),2)))
        rdos = pd.DataFrame(errores,columns=['alpha','error'])

        minimo = rdos.sort_values('error').alpha.values[0]

        plt.subplot(2,5,i+1)
        plt.plot(rdos.alpha,rdos.error,label='error')
        plt.vlines(x=minimo,ymin=min(rdos.error)-1,ymax=max(rdos.error),colors='r',linestyles='dashed',label='minimum')
        plt.legend(loc='lower right')
    plt.suptitle(f"{name} Model - Alpha Value vs Error",fontsize=30)
    plt.show()

models, names = [ElasticNet, LassoLars, Ridge ], ['ElasticNet', 'LassoLars', 'Ridge']

for a, b in zip(models,names):
    reg_output(model=a,name=b)

The observations that can be made from the plots are:

  • ElasticNet has an exponential distribution. Therefore, it's convenient the penalization to be as close as possible to zero.
  • LASSO reach it's minimum error on average around 0.2 and it tends to grow geometrically as the regularization term grows too.
  • Ridge has it's minimum error on average around 0.4 and it has the same distribution as LASSO.

Error¶

In this section we are using five datasets because we are describing the impact of different vector norms and therefore the unit of measure in each dataset is important for that matter.

The datasets that we are using are:

  • Market Arrivals, which is use to predict the quantity of people arriving at markets.
  • Mall Customers, which is use to predict the spending scores of customers.
  • Life Expectancy, which is use to predict the life expectancy of people.
  • Car, which is use to predict the sales of cars.
  • and College, which is use to predict students rates.

All of them were downloaded from https://github.com/selva86

From this dataframes we can see that the minimum preprocessing need it for them to be use for predicting are:

  • Null values treatment, for which in this case we are just going to delete those rows.
  • Categorical variables, must be converted to numerical.
  • The columns "CustomerID" must be eliminated from the Mall Customers dataframe.
  • And finally, all columns must be standardized.

Preprocessing¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder, MinMaxScaler

data = {}
url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/selva86/datasets/master/"
datasets = ['MarketArrivals','Mall_Customers_Int','Life_Expectancy_Data',
            'Carseats','College']
for dataset in datasets:
    data[dataset] = pd.read_csv(url+dataset+".csv")

ord_enc, scaler = OrdinalEncoder(), MinMaxScaler()
data['Mall_Customers_Int'].drop('CustomerID',axis=1,inplace=True)

for key in list(data.keys()):
    data[key].dropna(inplace=True)
    for col in data[key].columns:
        columnas = data[key].columns
        if data[key][col].dtype == 'O':
            data[key][col] = ord_enc.fit_transform(data[key][[col]])
    data[key] = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(data[key]),columns=columnas)
for key in list(data.keys()):
    print(data[key])

Now we see that the data is ready to be processed and we can use it to study the effect of each error measure in these datasets. For this purpose we wil use the Linear Regression function from Scikit Learn.

We are going to use the following error measures:

  • Max Error: $MAX = max_i(|x|_i)$
  • Mean Absolute Error: $MAE = \frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} |y_i - \hat{y_i}|$
  • Mean Square Error: $MSE = \frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2$
  • Root Square Mean Error: $RMSE = \sqrt{\frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2}$
  • Mean Absolute Percentage Error: $MAPE = \frac{1}{N} \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} \frac{|y_i - \hat{y_i}|}{y_i}$
  • R Squared: $R^2 = 1 - \frac{\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i - \hat{y_i})^2}{\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i - \bar{y_i})^2}$
  • Adjusted R Squared: $R^2_{adj} = 1 - \frac{(1-R^2)(N-1)}{N-k-1}$
In [ ]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from prettytable import PrettyTable
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

def mse(vector):
    a = sum(vector**2)/len(vector)
    return a

def r2(true,pred):
    mean = true.mean()
    a = 1 - (sum((true - pred)**2)/len(true))/(sum((true - mean)**2)/len(true))
    return a

def max_norm(vector):
    a = max(vector)
    return a

def p_norm(vector,p): # if p=1 its MAE or MAPE, if p=2 its RMSE
    a = (sum(abs(vector)**p)**(1/p))/100
    return a

def r2_adj(true,pred,k):
    mean = true.mean()
    a = 1 - (((len(true)-1) / (len(true)-k-1)) * (1 - (1 - (sum((true - pred)**2)/len(true))/(sum((true - mean)**2)/len(true)))))
    return a

# lr, errors = LinearRegression(), []
labels = ['quantity','Spending_Score','Life expectancy ','Sales','Grad.Rate']
for j in range(3):
    lr, errors = LinearRegression(), []
    for dataset, label in zip(datasets,labels):
        X, y = data[dataset].drop(label,axis=1), data[dataset][label]
        k = X.shape[1]
        X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.2)
        preds = lr.fit(X_train,y_train).predict(X_test)
        max_, mae, rmse, mape, mse_, r2_, r2adj_ = max_norm(y_test - preds), p_norm(y_test - preds,p=1), p_norm(y_test - preds,p=2), p_norm(abs(y_test - preds)/y_test,p=1), mse(y_test - preds), r2(y_test, preds), r2_adj(y_test,preds,k=k)
        errors.append((dataset, max_, mae, rmse, mape, mse_, r2_, r2adj_))

    errors = pd.DataFrame(errors)
    errors.set_index(0,inplace=True)
    errors.columns = ['max','mae','rmse','mape','mse','r2','r2adj']
    errors = errors.T

    x = PrettyTable()
    x.field_names = np.concatenate([['Metric'],errors.columns])
    for i in range(errors.shape[0]):
        x.add_row([errors.index[i].upper(),round(errors.iloc[i,0],4),round(errors.iloc[i,1],4),round(errors.iloc[i,2],4),round(errors.iloc[i,3],4),round(errors.iloc[i,4],4)])
    print(f"\nRun Number {j+1}")
    print(x)

Observations:

  • the max norm is sensitive to outliers and unit measure. Therefore is good to measure model's consistency. This means that the model tend to predict similarly with similar data.
  • the MAE, MSE and RMSE error measures are robust but they depend a lot of the unit of measure of different datasets. Among them only change the magnitude of the error. For example, MAE is always going to have the highest error.
  • MAPE is very robust because let us compare different datasets and models but it's very sensitive to bad data preprocessing.
  • Finally, r2 and adjusted r2 are very good to tell if the variables are good for the model. For example, with the life expectancy dataset we have a high value and always the smallest max value, a consistent MAPE, and the rests of the error measure (MAE, MSE and RMSE) shows consistency in all runs.

Linear Regression¶

In this final section we will see how the Linear Regression con be calculated not only importing libraies but also manually with vectors and matrices. For this purpose, we will do a simple linear regression which is when we have only one explanatory variables.

First of all, we will create two random variables $x$ and $y$ for this purpose. Finally, we will use vector algebra, matrix algebra and the Scikit Learn algorithm to print the intercept and the slope, which all will give the same result.

Simple Linear Regression

The model is the following:

$y = \alpha + \beta x_i$

where $\alpha$ is the intercept, $\beta$ the slope, $y$ the dependent variable and $x$ the explanatory variable. This also include an error term for each residual. Therefore, for each data pair we will have an error and the equation will be the following:

$y_i = \alpha + \beta x_i + \epsilon_i$

where $\epsilon$ is the error term.

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression as lr

y, x = np.random.randint(1,100,size=10), np.random.randint(1,100,size=10)
ones = [1] * len(y)
X = np.array([ones,x]).T
print(f"Dependent variable vector: {y}")
print(f"Explanatory variable vector: {x}")
print(f"Explanatory variable matrix: \n {X}")

In this case we will change the notation of the formula and we will call both the intercept and the slope as $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$ respectively.

Vector Algebra

$\beta_1 = \frac{\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (x_i - \bar{x_i})(y_i - \bar{y_i})}{\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{N} (x_i - \bar{x_i})^2}$

$\beta_0 = \bar{y} - \beta_1 \bar{x}$

Matrix Algebra

$\beta = (X^{T} X)^{-1} X^{t} Y$

In [ ]:
y_mean, x_mean = np.mean(y), np.mean(x)
num, den = (x - x_mean) * (y - y_mean), (x - x_mean)**2
b1 = np.sum(num)/np.sum(den)
b0 = y_mean - b1 * x_mean
print(f"Coefficients calculated with vectors: \n b0 = {round(b0,4)} \n b1 = {round(b1,4)} \n")

b = np.linalg.inv(X.T.dot(X)).dot(X.T).dot(y)
print(f"Coefficients calculated with matrix: \n b0 = {round(b[0],4)} \n b1 = {round(b[1],4)} \n")

model = lr().fit(X,y)
print(f"Coefficients calculated with scikit-learn algorith: \n b0 = {round(model.intercept_,4)} \n b1 = {round(model.coef_[1],4)}")
